## Rules

- Read relevant docs before asking or changing code
- Keep docs synchronized with code changes
- Never bypass git hooks with --no-verify or --force
- Never include secrets in commits, messages, or metadata
- Verify every change: npm run lint && npm run typecheck && npm run test

## Git Policy

- Branch from master, never push directly
- Use conventional commits: feat:, fix:, docs:, refactor:, test:, chore:
- One logical change per commit
- Atomic commits, PRs under 400 lines
- Modify the least possible files — 6-15 files = review needed, 30+ = wrong scope

## Read Before Working

Before any task, step through this sequence. Skip steps that do not match your task.

| Step | When | Read |
|------|------|------|
| 1 | ALWAYS | This file (AGENTS.md) |
| 2 | ALWAYS | docs/CODING_RULES.md — code rules and git policy |
| 3 | Creating or editing any .md file | docs/DOC_FORMATS.md |
| 4 | Changing architecture or boundaries | docs/decisions/README.md |
| 5 | Adding new files, dirs, or deps | docs/CONTEXT_STRATEGY.md |
| 6 | File creeping past 300 lines | docs/FILE_SIZE_RULEBOOK.md |
| 7 | Blocked by a design choice | docs/OPEN_QUESTIONS.md |

If you skip a step, state why. If a step's doc is missing, flag it as a defect.

## Quality Gates

Run before every commit:

```bash
npm run lint && npm run typecheck && npm run test
```

Failing a gate and proceeding is a defect.

## How To Ask Questions

Present 2-4 specific options. Mark recommended with "(Recommended)". Explain trade-offs.

## When To STOP

- Same concept may already exist
- New dependency is not clearly needed
- Intent is unclear and docs don't answer it

## Terminology

- Coding Agent = AI tool building this project
- Human Maintainer = person operating this project
